Question 4

pcadataset=princomp(dataset[,-5], cor=T) 
# Note that we take only the numerical columns to apply PCA.
# now pcadataset is a R object of type princomp

# To display the internal structure of pcadataset
str(pcadataset)

Question 5

#install.packages('factoextra')
library(factoextra)
## Warning: package 'factoextra' was built under R version 3.6.3
## Welcome! Want to learn more? See two factoextra-related books at https://goo.gl/ve3WBa
#Scree plot
fviz_eig(pcadataset)

# Graph of individuals
fviz_pca_ind(pcadataset,
col.ind = "contrib", # Color by their contribution to axes
gradient.cols = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "#FC4E07"),
repel = TRUE)

# Graph of variables
fviz_pca_var(pcadataset,
col.var = "contrib",
gradient.cols = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "#FC4E07"),
repel = TRUE)

# Biplot of individuals and variables
fviz_pca_biplot(pcadataset, repel = TRUE,
col.var = "#2E9FDF",
col.ind = "#696969")

#The contributions of the variables to the first 2 principal components
